  "prompt": "What is the nicest library at Columbia to work at?",
  "response": "That's a subjective question, and \"nicest\" depends on your priorities! Here's a breakdown of some of the most popular and well-regarded libraries at Columbia, with their strengths and weaknesses, to help you decide which is best for *you*:\n\n**For Iconic Beauty & Quiet Study:**\n\n*   **Butler Library (especially the Butler Library Reading Room):** This is probably the most famous and visually stunning. The Reading Room is breathtakingly beautiful and generally very quiet.\n    *   **Pros:** Grand architecture, high ceilings, lots of natural light (in the Reading Room), historically significant.\n    *   **Cons:** Can get crowded, especially during peak times (midterms/finals), limited outlets, specific rules in the Reading Room (very quiet). Not as convenient for group work.\n\n**For Focused Study & Extensive Resources:**\n\n*   **Lehman Social Sciences Library (International Affairs Building - IAB):** Known for its comprehensive collection of social science materials and its generally quiet atmosphere.\n    *   **Pros:** Excellent resources for social sciences, generally quiet, good individual study spaces.\n    *   **Cons:** Can feel a little sterile, less natural light than Butler.\n\n**For Collaborative Work & Modern Amenities:**\n\n*   **Science & Engineering Library (Seeley W. Mudd Building):** A good choice if you're looking for collaborative spaces and access to technology.\n    *   **Pros:** Group study rooms, access to computers and other technology, open study areas, more relaxed atmosphere than Butler.\n    *   **Cons:** Can be noisier than other libraries, focused on science and engineering resources.\n\n**For Specialized Collections & Intimate Atmosphere:**\n\n*   **Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library:** A beautiful space with a unique collection focused on architecture and art.\n    *   **Pros:** Gorgeous architecture, specialized collection, generally quieter than Butler.\n    *   **Cons:** Limited hours compared to Butler, only useful if your studies align with architecture or fine arts.\n\n*   **Burke Library at Union Theological Seminary:** Located just across the street from Columbia, it boasts beautiful architecture and a vast collection of theological materials, attracting students from diverse backgrounds.\n    *   **Pros:** A tranquil atmosphere conducive to focused study and reflection\n    *   **Cons:** Limited hours compared to Butler.\n\n**Factors to Consider When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your Field of Study:** Libraries have specific collections that are relevant to different fields. Use the library best suited to your coursework.\n*   **Your Study Style:** Do you prefer quiet, individual study, or collaborative work with a group?\n*   **Atmosphere:** Some libraries are grand and imposing, while others are more modern and relaxed.\n*   **Crowd Levels:** Butler can be incredibly busy during peak times. Consider libraries less popular.\n*   **Accessibility:** Consider the location of the library relative to your classes and housing.\n*   **Amenities:** Outlets, computer access, printing, food/drink policies.\n\n**My Recommendation:**\n\nThere's no single \"best\" library. I'd suggest visiting a few different ones and seeing which one feels most comfortable and conducive to your work.\n\nHere's what I'd suggest as a starting point:\n\n*   **For a first-time visitor:** Go to Butler Library Reading Room to experience the iconic beauty.\n*   **For serious, quiet study:** Lehman Library.\n*   **For group projects:** Science & Engineering Library.\n\n**Ultimately, the \"nicest\" library is the one where you can focus, be productive, and feel comfortable.** Good luck finding your favorite!\n",
